    <h1>How Much Protein Can You<br><span class="accent">Actually Absorb Per Meal?</span></h1>
    <p class="hero-sub">The 30g absorption limit is one of the most repeated myths in fitness. Here's what the science actually says — and why it matters more after 40.</p>
    <p class="hero-meta">By Robert · May 2, 2026 · 7 min read</p>
  </header>

  <main>

    <!-- QUICK ANSWER -->
    <div class="quick-answer">
      <h2>The Short Answer</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Your body absorbs <strong>nearly all the protein you eat</strong> — absorption is not the bottleneck</li>
        <li>The real question is how much protein your muscles can <strong>use for repair and growth</strong> in one sitting</li>
        <li>That threshold is approximately <strong>30–40g per meal</strong> — and men over 40 need the higher end</li>
        <li>Eating 60g at one meal isn't wasted — it's just used for other functions beyond muscle building</li>
        <li><strong>Spreading protein across 3–4 meals</strong> maximizes muscle stimulus — not because of absorption limits, but because of how muscle protein synthesis works</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- INTRO -->
    <p>I'm 64. For most of my life I assumed the "30g rule" meant my body physically couldn't absorb more than that at once — that anything extra was passing straight through unused. It's one of the most common things men over 40 believe about protein, and it shapes how they eat in ways that can actually work against them.</p>

    <p>The reality is more nuanced, and more useful. Your digestive system is remarkably efficient — it absorbs amino acids continuously and doesn't hit a hard wall at 30g. What researchers are actually talking about when they cite that number is something different: the dose required to maximally <em>stimulate</em> muscle protein synthesis. Those are two very different things, and confusing them leads to real mistakes in how you structure your eating.</p>

