        <div class="stat-label">daily meals hitting this threshold is the practical target for muscle maintenance</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>What "Absorption" Actually Means</h2>

    <p>Digestion works in stages. Protein you eat gets broken down by stomach acid and enzymes into amino acids, which are then absorbed through the wall of the small intestine into the bloodstream. This process is continuous — it doesn't stop at 30g and dump the rest. Your gut will keep working through whatever you give it, just at varying speeds depending on the protein source.</p>

    <p>The confusion comes from conflating two separate questions:</p>

    <div class="myth-fact-pair">
      <div class="myth-card">
        <div class="card-label">The Myth</div>
        <div class="card-text">Your body can only absorb 30g of protein per meal. Anything above that is wasted and passes through unused.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="fact-card">
        <div class="card-label">The Reality</div>
        <div class="card-text">Your body absorbs nearly all dietary protein regardless of dose. The 30g figure refers to the muscle stimulus threshold — not an absorption ceiling.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>So what actually happens to the protein above the muscle-building threshold? It gets used for other things your body needs protein for: enzymes, hormones, immune function, skin, hair, connective tissue. A small portion may be used for energy. Almost none of it is truly wasted — it's just redirected.</p>

    <h2>Digestion Speed: Why the Source Matters</h2>

    <p>Different protein sources digest at different rates, which affects how quickly amino acids appear in your bloodstream and how long they stay elevated. This matters because muscle protein synthesis requires amino acids to be available — specifically the branched-chain amino acid leucine, which acts as the trigger.</p>

