          <td>2–3 hours</td>
          <td>Lunch, dinner anchor</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Beef / pork</td>
          <td><span class="speed-med">Medium-slow</span></td>
          <td>3–4 hours</td>
          <td>Dinner, larger meals</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Casein / cottage cheese</td>
          <td><span class="speed-slow">Slow</span></td>
          <td>5–7 hours sustained</td>
          <td>Before bed, overnight</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Greek yogurt</td>
          <td><span class="speed-med">Medium</span></td>
          <td>2–3 hours</td>
          <td>Snack, pre-load</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>For men over 40, digestion speed matters more than it used to. Due to <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/" style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">anabolic resistance</a> — the reduced muscle sensitivity to protein signals that comes with age — having amino acids available across more hours of the day supports muscle maintenance better than one or two large protein doses. A fast-digesting protein earlier in the day and a slow-digesting source at night covers more of the 24-hour window.</p>

    <h2>The Muscle Stimulus Threshold — Why 30–40g Is the Right Target</h2>

    <p>Here's where the practical guidance lives. While absorption isn't the limiting factor, muscle protein synthesis is a triggered response — it requires a sufficient dose of amino acids to switch on. Below a certain threshold, the signal is weak. Above it, you've maximized the stimulus and additional protein in that meal contributes little extra benefit to muscle specifically.</p>

    <p>Research puts the effective dose for most adults at roughly 20–30g. For men over 40, the consensus is higher — <strong>30–40g per meal</strong> — because anabolic resistance means the muscle is less sensitive to the signal and needs a stronger dose to respond equivalently.</p>

    <div class="dose-grid">
      <div class="dose-card low">
        <div class="dose-num">10–20g</div>
        <div class="dose-verdict">Below threshold</div>
        <div class="dose-note">Protein is absorbed but muscle protein synthesis stimulus is weak or absent after 40</div>
      </div>
      <div class="dose-card mid">
        <div class="dose-num">30–40g</div>
        <div class="dose-verdict">Optimal zone</div>
        <div class="dose-note">Maximizes muscle protein synthesis stimulus per meal — the target for men over 40</div>
      </div>
      <div class="dose-card high">
        <div class="dose-num">60g+</div>
        <div class="dose-verdict">Absorbed, not wasted</div>
        <div class="dose-note">Fully absorbed and used for other functions — just no added muscle stimulus beyond the threshold</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>This is why a single 120g protein meal is not equivalent to four 30g meals. The total protein absorbed may be similar, but the muscle stimulus has only been triggered once instead of four times. For maintaining and building muscle after 40, frequency of stimulus matters alongside total intake.</p>

    <h2>What This Means in Practice</h2>

    <p>Two takeaways that should change how you structure your eating:</p>

    <p><strong>1. Don't skip meals and try to "catch up" at dinner.</strong> A 70g dinner doesn't give you twice the muscle benefit of a 35g dinner. It gives you roughly the same stimulus — with the extra protein redirected to other uses. The missed meals earlier in the day were lost stimulus opportunities you can't get back.</p>

    <p><strong>2. The goal is 3–4 meals each hitting 30–40g.</strong> Not one massive meal, not constant snacking — three or four clean protein anchors spread across the day. That's the pattern that keeps muscle protein synthesis active across most of your waking hours. If you want to see exactly what that looks like in real food, the <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/what-120g-protein-looks-like/" style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">120g visual breakdown</a> is the most useful reference on this site.</p>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <h3>The one-sentence version</h3>
      <p>Your body absorbs almost all the protein you eat — the question is never absorption, it's whether you gave your muscles enough at each meal to trigger repair, and whether you did it enough times throughout the day.</p>
    </div>

    <p>This connects directly to why visibility matters. Most men over 40 aren't eating zero protein — they're eating protein in patterns that don't align with how muscle protein synthesis actually works. They have a light breakfast, a moderate lunch, and a protein-heavy dinner. The dinner protein gets absorbed fine. But two of the day's four potential muscle stimulus windows were missed entirely.</p>

    <p>That's not a willpower problem. It's a visibility problem. When you can see your number at each meal — not just at the end of the day — the pattern becomes obvious and fixable. That's the whole idea behind <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/protein-pacing-strategy-men-over-40/" style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">protein pacing</a>, and it starts with understanding that absorption was never the constraint.</p>

